WEBVTT

1
00:01:15.728 --> 00:01:19.064
All her life she had wanted
to teach at Wellesley College.


2
00:01:19.232 --> 00:01:22.276
So when a position opened
in the Art History department...


3
00:01:22.443 --> 00:01:26.196
...she pursued it single-mindedly
until she was hired.


4
00:01:31.911 --> 00:01:34.121
It was whispered
that Katherine Watson...


5
00:01:34.581 --> 00:01:36.832
...a first-year teacher
from Oakland State...


6
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.252
...made up in brains
what she lacked in pedigree.


7
00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:53.348
Which was why this bohemian
from California...


8
00:01:53.516 --> 00:01:57.853
...was on her way to the most
conservative college in the nation.


9
00:01:58.021 --> 00:02:00.606
-Excuse me, please.
-Oh, sorry.


10
00:02:02.317 --> 00:02:03.984
Excuse me.

11
00:02:08.489 --> 00:02:10.324
Excuse me. The bus?

12
00:02:10.491 --> 00:02:12.201
-Keep walking, ma'am.
-Thank you.


13
00:02:12.368 --> 00:02:16.121
But Katherine Watson didn't come
to Wellesley to fit in.


14
00:02:16.664 --> 00:02:20.751
She came to Wellesley because
she wanted to make a difference.


15
00:02:20.919 --> 00:02:24.546
-Violet.
-My favorite Italian professor.


16
00:02:24.714 --> 00:02:26.673
-Nice summer?
-Terrific, thanks.


17
00:02:26.841 --> 00:02:29.009
-Who's that over there?
-Where?


18
00:02:29.177 --> 00:02:33.847
Oh, Katherine Watson. New teacher.
Art History. I'm dying to meet her.


19
00:03:35.285 --> 00:03:38.161
Who knocks at the Door of Learning?

20
00:03:38.329 --> 00:03:42.874
-I am every woman.
-What do you seek?


21
00:03:43.042 --> 00:03:45.669
To awaken my spirit
through hard work...


22
00:03:45.837 --> 00:03:48.088
...and dedicate my life
to knowledge.


23
00:03:48.256 --> 00:03:49.715
Then you are welcome.

24
00:03:49.882 --> 00:03:54.970
All women who seek to follow you
can enter here.


25
00:03:55.138 --> 00:03:59.891
I now declare
the academic year begun.


26
00:04:19.078 --> 00:04:23.623
A shame you didn't come yesterday.
It's so quiet before the girls arrive.


27
00:04:26.336 --> 00:04:29.713
Just a few rules.
No holes in the walls.


28
00:04:29.881 --> 00:04:34.509
No pets, no loud noises, no radio
or hi-fi after 8 on weekdays...


29
00:04:34.677 --> 00:04:36.386
...10 on weekends...

30
00:04:36.554 --> 00:04:40.015
...no hot plates and no male visitors.

31
00:04:42.435 --> 00:04:43.977
Anything wrong?

32
00:04:44.896 --> 00:04:48.440
I don't think I can go a year
without a hot plate.


33
00:04:52.570 --> 00:04:55.572
Don't you just love chintz?

34
00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:57.616
And look.

35
00:05:01.621 --> 00:05:03.455
They match.

36
00:05:03.623 --> 00:05:07.542
Sweet, right? Your room's here.

37
00:05:07.710 --> 00:05:11.755
My room is just across the way...

38
00:05:12.298 --> 00:05:15.008
...and Amanda Armstrong's
down the other end.


39
00:05:15.635 --> 00:05:18.303
-You grew up here?
-My whole life.


40
00:05:18.471 --> 00:05:22.307
You'll meet my parents
when they come to visit.


41
00:05:22.475 --> 00:05:25.811
-They visit?
-Regularly.


42
00:05:28.314 --> 00:05:33.985
-What do you teach?
-Speech, elocution and poise.


43
00:05:34.404 --> 00:05:36.822
Dinners are communal,
so I'll handle that.


44
00:05:36.989 --> 00:05:40.617
But breakfast and lunch,
you're on your own. So...


45
00:05:40.785 --> 00:05:45.831
...we each get our own shelf.
I'll make your label this evening.


46
00:05:46.290 --> 00:05:52.212
I don't need to tell you, everything on
our individual shelves is sacrosanct.


47
00:05:54.048 --> 00:05:57.717
I just knew when we met...

48
00:05:58.636 --> 00:06:01.012
...we'd be instant friends.

49
00:06:19.198 --> 00:06:23.743
Be careful. They can smell fear.

50
00:06:44.056 --> 00:06:46.892
-Good morning.
-Good morning.


51
00:06:47.226 --> 00:06:48.894
Thank you.

52
00:06:49.645 --> 00:06:54.524
This is History of Art 100.

53
00:06:55.067 --> 00:06:59.112
We'll be following
Dr. Staunton's syllabus.


54
00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:02.240
-Any questions so far?
-Your name?


55
00:07:03.242 --> 00:07:05.619
-Why don't you go first?
-Connie Baker.


56
00:07:05.786 --> 00:07:10.457
-Katherine Watson. Nice to meet you.
-Dr. Watson, I presume.


57
00:07:11.584 --> 00:07:14.794
-Not yet. And you are?
-Giselle Levy.


58
00:07:14.962 --> 00:07:17.547
Giselle. If someone could get the--

59
00:07:18.799 --> 00:07:22.761
-Susan Delacorte.
-Thank you, Susan Delacorte.


60
00:07:26.265 --> 00:07:31.186
From the beginning, man has always
had the impulse to create art.


61
00:07:31.354 --> 00:07:34.773
-Can anyone tell me what this is?
-Wounded Bison, Altamira, Spain...


62
00:07:34.941 --> 00:07:38.235
...about 15,000 B.C.
Joan Brandwyn.


63
00:07:38.694 --> 00:07:40.612
Very good, Joan.

64
00:07:40.947 --> 00:07:44.950
Despite the age of these, they are
technically sophisticated because--


65
00:07:45.117 --> 00:07:49.621
The shading and the thickness of the
lines moving over the bison's hump.


66
00:07:49.789 --> 00:07:53.750
-Is that right?
-Yes, that's exactly right.


67
00:07:54.502 --> 00:07:56.503
Next slide.

68
00:07:57.046 --> 00:08:01.132
This is probably less familiar.
It was discovered by archeologists--


69
00:08:01.300 --> 00:08:05.262
In 1879, Lascaux, France.
Dates back to 10,000 B.C.


70
00:08:05.429 --> 00:08:09.724
Singled out because of flowing lines
depicting the movement of the animal.


71
00:08:11.852 --> 00:08:14.604
-Impressive. Name?
-Herd of Horses.


72
00:08:14.772 --> 00:08:17.983
-I meant yours.
-We call her Flicka.


73
00:08:18.609 --> 00:08:21.361
Elizabeth Warren.
They call me Betty.


74
00:08:21.529 --> 00:08:23.154
Very good.

75
00:08:23.322 --> 00:08:25.991
Betty is also correct.

76
00:08:26.158 --> 00:08:30.036
Just because something is ancient
doesn't mean that it is primitive.


77
00:08:30.204 --> 00:08:32.455
For example. Next slide, please.

78
00:08:32.623 --> 00:08:35.125
Mycerinus and His Queen. 2470 B.C.

79
00:08:35.293 --> 00:08:37.794
It's a funerary statue
of the pharaoh and queen...


80
00:08:37.962 --> 00:08:42.257
...originally intended to preserve
the pharaoh's KA. Soul.


81
00:08:45.845 --> 00:08:48.763
Have any of you taken
Art History before?


82
00:08:48.931 --> 00:08:51.182
No.

83
00:08:53.894 --> 00:08:56.521
Let's go on. Slide.

84
00:08:56.856 --> 00:08:59.774
Seated Scribe. Egypt. 2400 B.C.

85
00:09:00.693 --> 00:09:04.362
Peasant Couple Plowing.
Sixteenth century B.C. Egypt.


86
00:09:04.989 --> 00:09:08.074
Snake Goddess.
Minoan. 1600 B.C.


87
00:09:08.868 --> 00:09:10.785
Fresco. Minoan. 1600 B.C.

88
00:09:11.704 --> 00:09:13.872
Funeral Mask. Mycenaean. 1200.

89
00:09:26.218 --> 00:09:27.594
Could someone please get--?

90
00:09:34.393 --> 00:09:36.061
Thank you.

91
00:09:37.605 --> 00:09:41.024
By a show of hands only...

92
00:09:41.859 --> 00:09:46.029
...how many of you have read
the entire text?


93
00:09:48.491 --> 00:09:53.870
-And the suggested supplements.
-Long way from Oakland State?


94
00:09:57.291 --> 00:09:59.751
Well, you girls do prepare.

95
00:09:59.919 --> 00:10:03.672
If you've nothing else for us,
we could go to independent study.


96
00:10:04.590 --> 00:10:06.216
Ac--

97
00:10:42.962 --> 00:10:49.092
I was in California once. How do you
get work done with all that sunshine?


98
00:10:49.427 --> 00:10:53.054
-We tan in class.
-Really?


99
00:10:53.305 --> 00:10:54.639
No.

100
00:10:58.936 --> 00:11:01.521
You know, not everybody
wanted you.


101
00:11:01.689 --> 00:11:04.190
I'm not naming any names.

102
00:11:04.358 --> 00:11:08.987
These jobs usually go quickly.
Ex-students, friends of, you know...


103
00:11:09.155 --> 00:11:11.489
...the right people.

104
00:11:11.657 --> 00:11:15.577
The person they wanted took a job at
Brown, and no one else was available.


105
00:11:15.745 --> 00:11:17.829
So here you are.

106
00:11:18.664 --> 00:11:22.500
You can go in now. Good luck.

107
00:11:28.507 --> 00:11:31.301
Your first class left a lot
to be desired, Miss Watson.


108
00:11:31.469 --> 00:11:35.138
And I'm curious about the subject
of your dissertation.


109
00:11:35.306 --> 00:11:40.226
You suggest, "Picasso will do
for the 20th century...


110
00:11:40.394 --> 00:11:44.355
...what Michelangelo did
for the Renaissance," unquote.


111
00:11:45.107 --> 00:11:47.567
In terms of influencing movements.

112
00:11:47.735 --> 00:11:50.945
So these canvases that
they're turning out these days...


113
00:11:51.113 --> 00:11:54.199
...with paint dripped
and splotched on them...


114
00:11:54.366 --> 00:11:59.329
...they're as worthy of our attention
as Michelangelo's Sistine Chapel?


115
00:11:59.872 --> 00:12:01.664
I'm not comparing them.

116
00:12:01.832 --> 00:12:05.460
Have you ever seen
the Sistine Chapel, Miss Watson?


117
00:12:05.628 --> 00:12:07.629
Actually stood there?

118
00:12:09.256 --> 00:12:11.132
I've never been to Europe.

119
00:12:14.386 --> 00:12:19.224
I can assure all of you this is the place
I want to be more than anything.


120
00:12:19.391 --> 00:12:23.895
Better discipline next class,
Miss Watson.


121
00:12:29.235 --> 00:12:31.444
-Hello.
-It's me.


122
00:12:31.946 --> 00:12:34.656
-Hey!
-Collect from Katherine Watson.


123
00:12:34.824 --> 00:12:38.409
-Will you accept?
-Yeah, sure, of course I will.


124
00:12:39.036 --> 00:12:41.246
Hey, is everything okay?

125
00:12:42.498 --> 00:12:43.498
Yeah.

126
00:12:44.792 --> 00:12:46.417
Tough, huh?

127
00:12:49.505 --> 00:12:52.006
Well, how are the classes?

128
00:12:52.633 --> 00:12:54.592
Snobs, right?

129
00:12:55.886 --> 00:12:59.973
-I hate to say I told you so.
-You don't have to.


130
00:13:06.522 --> 00:13:08.648
I can't really talk right now.

131
00:13:09.859 --> 00:13:11.776
I'll write you tonight.

132
00:13:15.948 --> 00:13:17.448
So you got a fella?

133
00:13:18.909 --> 00:13:22.120
He's-
- He's there. I'm here.

134
00:13:22.288 --> 00:13:27.792
Long distance. Torture. I know.
Come. Come in and sit down.


135
00:13:31.463 --> 00:13:35.633
When Lenny left for the South Pacific,
it nearly broke my heart.


136
00:13:35.801 --> 00:13:38.511
We wrote every day until....

137
00:13:41.181 --> 00:13:43.308
He was a great man.

138
00:13:44.101 --> 00:13:47.020
-I'm sorry.
-It was a hundred years ago.


139
00:13:47.187 --> 00:13:48.980
I'm babbling.

140
00:13:51.233 --> 00:13:56.279
I love Lucy.
Even if she is a communist.


141
00:13:56.447 --> 00:13:59.324
The only thing red about Lucy
is her hair.


142
00:13:59.491 --> 00:14:01.951
And even that's fake. Desi said it.

143
00:14:02.119 --> 00:14:04.037
Winchell wrote it.

144
00:14:04.830 --> 00:14:07.749
Amanda Armstrong.
I see you survived.


145
00:14:07.917 --> 00:14:09.792
Katherine Watson. Just barely.

146
00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:13.087
Oh, good. You've met.
Katherine's taken the third bedroom.


147
00:14:13.255 --> 00:14:16.257
How about a little dinner
before What's My Line?


148
00:14:17.301 --> 00:14:19.844
How about a little drink?

149
00:14:22.181 --> 00:14:25.016
Her companion died in May.

150
00:14:25.559 --> 00:14:26.893
Companion?

151
00:14:27.728 --> 00:14:30.104
You know, companion.

152
00:14:31.231 --> 00:14:37.236
Josephine Burns.
Taught biology here for 30 years.


153
00:14:40.616 --> 00:14:43.743
You'll love it here, Katherine.
You'll see.


154
00:14:43.911 --> 00:14:48.873
I already do. I-- Honestly,
it's beautiful. It's perfect, really.


155
00:14:49.041 --> 00:14:53.586
Well, don't fool yourself. They have
claws underneath their white gloves.


156
00:14:54.880 --> 00:14:56.381
Who?

157
00:14:57.174 --> 00:15:01.719
The alumnae, their offspring,
the faculty. You name it.


158
00:15:02.054 --> 00:15:03.888
Watch out for yourself.

159
00:15:04.056 --> 00:15:06.099
Too much independence
frightens them.


160
00:15:06.266 --> 00:15:10.061
-Will you please stop?
-Oh, a word of advice.


161
00:15:10.229 --> 00:15:13.606
Don't let those girls
know that they got to you.


162
00:15:16.110 --> 00:15:19.195
-They didn't.
-Good for you.


163
00:15:20.656 --> 00:15:22.907
You almost convinced me.

164
00:15:53.272 --> 00:15:56.190
-What is that?
-You tell me.


165
00:15:59.611 --> 00:16:03.448
Carcass by Soutine. 1925.

166
00:16:04.408 --> 00:16:07.910
-It's not on the syllabus.
-No, it's not.


167
00:16:09.913 --> 00:16:12.165
Is it any good?

168
00:16:17.421 --> 00:16:22.050
Come on, ladies.
There's no wrong answer.


169
00:16:22.217 --> 00:16:25.720
There's also no textbook
telling you what to think.


170
00:16:26.722 --> 00:16:28.806
It's not that easy, is it?

171
00:16:29.892 --> 00:16:32.226
All right. No. 
It's not good.

172
00:16:32.394 --> 00:16:35.188
In fact, I wouldn't even call it art.
It's grotesque.


173
00:16:35.397 --> 00:16:37.273
Is there a rule against
grotesque art?


174
00:16:37.483 --> 00:16:40.943
I think there's something
aggressive about it...


175
00:16:41.653 --> 00:16:44.822
-...and erotic.
-To you, everything is erotic.


176
00:16:44.990 --> 00:16:47.408
-Everything is erotic.
-Girls.


177
00:16:47.576 --> 00:16:49.827
-Aren't there standards?
-Of course.


178
00:16:49.995 --> 00:16:53.331
Otherwise a tacky velvet painting
could be equated to a Rembrandt.


179
00:16:53.499 --> 00:16:57.710
My Uncle Ferdie has two tacky velvet
paintings. He loves those clowns.


180
00:16:57.878 --> 00:17:03.633
There are standards, technique,
composition, color, even subject.


181
00:17:03.801 --> 00:17:06.803
So if you're suggesting
that rotted side of meat is art...


182
00:17:06.970 --> 00:17:10.139
...much less good art,
then what are we going to learn?


183
00:17:11.308 --> 00:17:12.850
Just that.

184
00:17:13.018 --> 00:17:16.604
You have outlined our new syllabus,
Betty. Thank you.


185
00:17:16.772 --> 00:17:19.690
What is art?
What makes it good or bad?


186
00:17:19.858 --> 00:17:21.818
And who decides?

187
00:17:22.778 --> 00:17:24.237
Next slide, please.

188
00:17:26.281 --> 00:17:29.367
Twenty-five years ago someone
thought this was brilliant.


189
00:17:29.535 --> 00:17:31.786
-I can see that.
-Who?


190
00:17:31.954 --> 00:17:35.498
My mother. I painted it
for her birthday.


191
00:17:35.666 --> 00:17:39.877
Next slide. This is my mom.

192
00:17:40.462 --> 00:17:43.756
-Is it art?
-It's a snapshot.


193
00:17:43.924 --> 00:17:47.885
If I told you Ansel Adams had taken it,
would that make a difference?


194
00:17:48.929 --> 00:17:53.349
-Art isn't art until someone says it is.
-It's art!


195
00:17:54.601 --> 00:17:57.353
-The right people.
-Who are they?


196
00:17:57.563 --> 00:17:58.896
Betty Warren!

197
00:17:59.064 --> 00:18:02.650
-We're lucky we have one right here.
-Screw you.


198
00:18:04.444 --> 00:18:06.821
Could you go back
to the Soutine, please?


199
00:18:09.158 --> 00:18:13.202
Just look at it again.
Look beyond the paint.


200
00:18:13.370 --> 00:18:18.249
Let us try to open our minds
to a new idea.


201
00:18:21.170 --> 00:18:25.256
All right, back to chapter three.
Has anyone read it?


202
00:18:27.509 --> 00:18:28.551
Okay.

203
00:18:31.930 --> 00:18:34.891
"When your courses are set,
and a dream boat you've met...


204
00:18:35.058 --> 00:18:37.101
...have a real cigarette.
Have a Camel."


205
00:18:37.269 --> 00:18:41.272
I've got my courses, I've got my Camel
cigarette. Where is my dream boat?


206
00:18:41.440 --> 00:18:44.984
-Giselle, where is my dream boat?
-Betty's cousin isn't good enough?


207
00:18:45.152 --> 00:18:47.195
-I haven't met him.
-Don't encourage her.


208
00:18:47.362 --> 00:18:49.947
He's only escorting
Connie as a favor.


209
00:18:50.115 --> 00:18:52.033
Why are you like this?

210
00:18:52.701 --> 00:18:54.785
I didn't mean that.

211
00:18:54.953 --> 00:18:57.622
I'm just under so much pressure
with the wedding.


212
00:18:57.789 --> 00:19:00.791
Do you realize November 2nd
is three weeks from now?


213
00:19:00.959 --> 00:19:02.877
-Oh, honey.
-Don't have it.


214
00:19:03.045 --> 00:19:04.670
-Don't come.
-Here. Here.


215
00:19:04.838 --> 00:19:08.049
I'm working on table seating now,
so I can just erase your name.


216
00:19:08.217 --> 00:19:09.467
-Can I see it?
-No.


217
00:19:09.635 --> 00:19:11.677
Let me look.
I can't look for a second?


218
00:19:11.845 --> 00:19:15.264
-You want to see where Bill is sitting.
-No. That is over. Right?


219
00:19:15.432 --> 00:19:18.100
Right? Giselle, right?

220
00:19:20.103 --> 00:19:21.646
Damn it.

221
00:19:27.653 --> 00:19:31.155
-Do I look a little bit like her?
-Like who?


222
00:19:31.657 --> 00:19:35.117
-Katherine Watson.
-You mean, "crap is art"?


223
00:19:35.827 --> 00:19:40.122
-I think she's fabulous.
-Well, no man wanted her.


224
00:19:41.500 --> 00:19:43.668
-She isn't dead.
-She's at least 30.


225
00:19:43.835 --> 00:19:46.921
-Oh, no. No.
-I guess she never wanted children.


226
00:19:47.089 --> 00:19:49.006
For your information...

227
00:19:49.174 --> 00:19:55.221
...Katherine Watson had to take
this job to escape from California.


228
00:19:55.931 --> 00:19:57.181
Please.

229
00:19:57.349 --> 00:20:01.269
She had a torrid affair
with a Hollywood movie star.


230
00:20:01.436 --> 00:20:05.773
-She came here to get away.
-That's ridiculous.


231
00:20:05.941 --> 00:20:08.693
-Who was it?
-I don't know.


232
00:20:09.152 --> 00:20:11.737
Who was it, Giselle?
Don't be a pimple! Tell me!


233
00:20:11.905 --> 00:20:14.615
-It's ridiculous.
-Tell me. No, it's not. You know.


234
00:20:14.783 --> 00:20:18.411
-You know something. Tell me.
-It's William Holden.


